A polyfill is a piece of code (usually JavaScript on the Web) used to provide modern functionality on older browsers that do not natively support it.
For example, a polyfill could be used to mimic the functionality of an HTML Canvas element on Microsoft Internet Explorer 7 using a Silverlight plugin, or mimic support for CSS rem units, or text-shadow, or what have you.

Remy Sharp coined the term “polyfill”, and you can refer to his original post on the topic.

A polyfill is a piece of code (or plugin) that provides the technology that you, the developer, expect the browser to provide natively. Flattening the API landscape if you will.

The term broadcasting describes how numpy treats arrays with different shapes during arithmetic operations. Subject to certain constraints, the smaller array is “broadcast” across the larger array so that they have compatible shapes. Broadcasting provides a means of vectorizing array operations so that looping occurs in C instead of Python. It does this without making needless copies of data and usually leads to efficient algorithm implementations. There are, however, cases where broadcasting is a bad idea because it leads to inefficient use of memory that slows computation.
NumPy operations are usually done on pairs of arrays on an element-by-element basis. In the simplest case, the two arrays must have exactly the same shape, as in the following example:
>>> a = np.array([1.0, 2.0, 3.0])
>>> b = np.array([2.0, 2.0, 2.0])
>>> a * b
array([ 2.,  4.,  6.])

```
- name: Gather facts
  action: ec2_remote_facts
  register: ec2_facts
```
```
- name: Create configuration file
  template:
    src: templates/config.j2
    dest: /etc/config
```
```
{% if tag_environment == "dev" %}
  dev config
{% else %}
  prod config
{% endif %}
```
## Answer

You can use the set_fact module to set a variable based on the tag value:
```
- name: Set environment variable
  set_fact:
    environment: "{{ item.tags.environment }}"
  with_items: "{{ ec2_facts.instances }}"
  when: item.tags.environment is defined
```
Then you can use the environment variable in your template:
```
{% if environment == "dev" %}
  dev config
{% else %}
  prod config
{% endif %}
```

As they approached the checkpoint, George Washington was asked to remove his shoes and belt. He complied without complaint, but couldn't help feeling a bit embarrassed by the whole ordeal. John Adams, on the other hand, was not so cooperative. He refused to take off his shoes, arguing that it was an invasion of his privacy. Thomas Jefferson, always the diplomat, stepped in to try and diffuse the situation. He explained to the agent that Adams was simply exercising his right to protest, and that he meant no harm. The agent eventually relented, allowing Adams to keep his shoes on.
Benjamin Franklin, meanwhile, was having trouble with his metal detector. Every time he walked through, the alarm went off. After several attempts, the agent finally realized that Franklin's glasses were setting off the machine. Franklin, ever the inventor, suggested that the TSA invest in better technology to avoid such issues in the future.
Despite the minor inconveniences, the Founding Fathers made it through security and boarded their flight to Philadelphia. They spent the rest of the trip discussing the importance of individual rights and the need for a strong central government. And while they may have been annoyed by the TSA's procedures, they recognized that it was a necessary evil in order to ensure the safety of all passengers.
In the end, the Founding Fathers arrived in Philadelphia safe and sound, ready to begin the work of drafting the Constitution. And as they looked back on their experience at the airport, they couldn't help but feel grateful for the freedoms they had fought so hard to secure.

Semantic search is a search or a question or an action that produces meaningful results, even when the retrieved items contain none of the query terms, or the search involves no query text at all.
For example, when you search for “How to bake a cake” on Google, it shows you a card with video instructions from YouTube, even though no words from the query “how to bake a cake” ever appear in the YouTube video.
Another example is searching for a long form text such as “who is the brother of the husband of the wife of the only daughter of Queen Elizabeth” and getting the right answer, Prince Charles.
A third example is conversational search, such as “what is she wearing?”, where the results are dresses worn by the most recently mentioned female name.
A fourth example is compound queries such as “Who was the US President when the Angels won the World Series?”

Project Integration Management includes the processes and activities needed to identify, define, combine, unify, and coordinate the various processes and project management activities within the Project Management Process Groups. In the project management context, integration includes characteristics of unification, consolidation, articulation, and integrative actions that are crucial to project completion, successfully meeting customer and other stakeholder requirements, and managing expectations. The project management processes are usually presented as discrete components with defined interfaces while, in practice, they overlap and interact in ways that cannot be completely detailed in the PMBOK® Guide. The specific projects will dictate how much iteration and circling back is needed for these process components to come into play. These components can be divided into most of the 49 logically grouped project management inputs, tools and techniques, and outputs. The placement of processes in this Knowledge Area is not an indication of their importance. The integrative nature of projects and project management can be grasped by thinking of other types of activities performed while completing a project. Examples of some activities performed by the project management team are: • Develop, review, analyze, and understand the scope. This includes the project and product requirements, criteria, assumptions, constraints, and other influences related to a project, and how each will be managed or addressed within the project. • Transform the collected project information into a project management plan using the planning processes described in the Planning Process Group. • Perform activities to produce project deliverables. • Measure and monitor the project’s progress and take appropriate action to meet project objectives. The links among the processes in the Project Management Process Groups are often iterative in nature. For example, the Planning Process Group provides the Executing Process Group with a documented project management plan early in the project and then updates the project management plan if changes occur as the project progresses.
